  "prompt": "Can Trump revoke the same-sex marriage law?",
  "response": "As of my last update in October 2023, the legality of same-sex marriage in the United States is established by the Supreme Court ruling in Obergefell v. Hodges (2015). This ruling determined that same-sex marriage is a constitutional right under the 14th Amendment. \n\nFormer President Donald Trump, or any president for that matter, does not have the power to unilaterally revoke Supreme Court decisions or laws. Changes to such rulings would typically require either a new Supreme Court decision overturning the precedent or a constitutional amendment, which is a complex process requiring significant support from both houses of Congress and three-fourths of the states.\n\nWhile the president can influence judicial appointments and advocate for certain policies, directly revoking established Supreme Court decisions exceeding the authority of the presidential office.",
